Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

Your code is **Timeout enforcement** — it aborts a thread that exceeds a time limit. All three deprecated APIs are present:

| API Found | Status in .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate MUST check the CancellationToken for timely cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### If you also need the original `Func<T>` overload (fire-and-forget uncooperative work):

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Overload for work that cannot accept a CancellationToken.
/// WARNING: The work continues running in the background after timeout —
/// it is NOT killed. Only use when the work is side-effect-free or
/// you accept the background execution.
/// </summary>
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(work); // no token — work can't cooperate

    try
    {
        // .NET 6+ API: wait for the task but cancel the wait on timeout
        task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }

    return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work keeps running after "timeout"** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cooperative cancellation **cannot kill** running code. If `work` ignores the token, it runs to completion in the background. This is the biggest behavioral change. |
| **Must pass token through the full chain** | Every method called by `work` must accept and forward the `CancellationToken`. One method that ignores it blocks cancellation at that point. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` won't cancel** | Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` inside work with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `await Task.Delay(ms, token)`. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer leaks. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch timeout-caused cancellations, not caller-initiated ones. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If the work is third-party code that cannot accept a token, the only way to forcibly stop it is to move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET. |

## Example Caller Migration

**Before (.NET Framework):**
```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveResult(data),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**After (.NET 8):**
```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => ComputeExpensiveResult(data, ct),  // pass token into work
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// The work method must cooperate:
int ComputeExpensiveResult(Data data, CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var item in data.Items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return data.Items.Count;
}
```

The fundamental shift: **you** are now responsible for stopping work at checkpoints — the runtime will no longer do it for you.
